{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/00279558388/1937122801/0487.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER\nCloudy and unsettled tonight\nand Wednesday with probable\n'\u2022*ht rains. Colder tomorrow.\n(Elti4 \u00a9tntes Jfettrs\nLargest Daily Circulation of Any Newspaper i n North Carolina in Proportion to Population\nGOOD AFTERNOON\nAhout now any Dad it consid\nering hanging up that birthday\nnecktie to he can wear hit Chriit*\nmn present.\nVOL. 56\u2014No. 309\nHENDERSON VILLE, N. C., TUESDAY, DECEMBER 28, 1937\nSINGLE COPIES, FIVE CENTS\nFIRM\nSTAND BY F. R.\n9 *9*\nChinese Bomb Jap Launch At Shanghai\nINCIDENT !S\n2ND OF KIND\nPAST 24 HOIJRS\nFollows Japanese Army\nEdict for Punishment\nin Interference\nAMERICANS READY\nTO DEPART TSINGTAO\nSHANGHAI. Dec (UP)\n1 taring Chinese grenadiers today\nbombed a Japanese army launch\nin Sooehuv cteek for the sccond\ntime in 21 hours.\nThree men stood on a bt idge\nand dropped a grenade as the\nlaunch parsed under, wounding\none Japanese. The us-ailants van\ndied in the crowd.\nJapanese searched vainly and\nShanghai municipal police weres\u00ab\u00bb\nalarmed that thev closed all but\nfour Sooehow bridges and stopped\ntraffic on them whenever a .Japa\nnese launch passed.\nThe attacks followed promulga\ntion by the Japanese their dras\ntic regulations prescribing death\npenalty for any one, including\nAmericans, guilty of molesting the\nJapanese army or navy in occu\npied territory.\nJapanese admitted today that,\nthough Shanghai and Nanking\nwere taken, the inierlying coun\ntry is honeycombed with strong\nbands of Chinese giie* ilia fighters,\ncausing considerable :\u00bbnn >yance.\nMachine-gun fir in*? wa- plainly\nheard in the -tiburi s. indicating\nproximity of bands of these Chi\nnese.\nThe Chinese admitted Tsinan.\ncapital of the province of Shan\ntung. hatl fallen.\nAt Tokyo, Japanese foreign\nminister Koki Hirota hand<-d the\nl.ritish ambassador. Robert C'rai\ngie. a reply to Ilriti h protests in\nthe bombing of th\u00abi gunboat Lady\nbird. It reported thh reply was\nsimilar to the reply *o th\u00ab* I r.ited\nStates protests in th Panay inci\ndent. The text of the note wa<\nnot made public.\nAMERICANS READY\nTO QUIT TSINGTAO\nCopyright. 1937, by United I' rfii\nTSINGTAO. Dec. 28. (UP)\nAmerican* and other fnn'i|(noi>\nprepared to f!\u00ab\u2022** th-.' ;:reat port\ncity of Tsingtao today rumors\nspread that th\u00ab municipal govern\nment. including the police, plan\nned to evacuate in the face of\napproaching Japanese armies, and\nleave thr ci\u00bbv in a state Ixirderini;\n\u00ab>n anarchy.\nThe American gunboat Sacra\nim-nta was scheduled to leave for\nShanghai with 27 Americans,\nmostly women and children. There\nare about :{uo Americans in Tsing\ntao.\nForeigners eontcmplatcd setting\nup an emergency vigilante corps\nto retain sonic semblance of law\nand order until Japanese troops,\ndriving southeastward from the\nYellow river, arrive to take over\nthe city's government\nCHINESE ADMITTING\nSHANTUNG RETREAT\nSHANGHAI. IVc. 28. (I P\u00bb\nChinese military sources said to\nday that the Chinese army was in\nfull retreat in Shanttmsr province,\nafter Japanese smashed through\nthe last defenses at the capital\ncity of Tsinan. completely occupy\ning the stronghold.\nThe reports said Chinese force-;\nhad blown up utility plants and\ndestroyed communication lines as\nthey fled from the city.\nThe Japanese were reported\ndriving southeastward toward th<(\nShantung coast, threatening to\nbottle up the Chinese forces de\nfending Tsingtao, where there arc\nmore than 1.000 foreigners, in\ncluding .100 Americans.\nChinese reports said the Chi\nnese armies had fled toward th\u00ab*\nhills, hoping to lure the Japanese\ninto rugjred, unfamiliar country\nwhere they could employ guerilla\ntactics.\nSAME GIRL IN TWO\nPORTS, BRITON WANTS\nHER TO RETURN HOME\nNEW ORLEANS. Die. 28.\n(UP)\u2014The \"international ro\nmance\" of Jack Tricker, sailor\naboard H.M.S. Orion, became com\nplicated yesterday when he found\nthe same srirl in two ports. Mobile\npolice asked local officers to find\n16-year-old Martha Redding and\nsend her home. Tricker said he\nhad two dates with her while the\ncruiser was in Mobile but when\nshe appeared in this port, he suk\njrested that she go home.\nSon Horn After\nHis Mother Died\nAlive and well is the IVi\u00abpound\npostmortem haby son, shown\nal>ove in a respirator, who was\ntak\u00ab'\u00bb from his mother. Mrs. Mar\ngaret lieaver Newton, wife of a\nWyoming rancher, iust one min\nute after she in a Cheyenne\nhospital. Physicians, who worked\nwith lightning speed to >ave the\nDEATH TAKES\nt B. HUDSON\nDairyman Here Expires at\n1 P. M. Following\nHeart Attack\n\\V. Hudson, operator of Hud\nson's ilairy and a resident of the\nClear (\"reck road. died this after\nnoon at t o'clock following ji heart\nattack which he had suffered three\nhours previously.\nIt wa.s stated that funeral ser\nvices would not be arranged until\nthe arrival of a son. Ralph, who\nhas been making his home in Stu\nart. Fla.. for several months, but\nthat the funeral woubl likely be\non Thursday afternoon.\n.Mr. Hudson had been an invalid\nfrom heart trouble for about three\nyen lli< attack this morning\nwas suddet and he had been up\nand about during the morning.\nHe was n native of tlm county.\n.Mr. Hudson leaves his wife, and\nanother son beside the one men\ntinned. Rudolph, who makes his\nhome here.\nCZECH CONSUL DIES\nCHICAGO, Dec. 2H.\u2014 (UP)\nJaroslav F. Smetanka, JiG, consul\ngeneral for Czechoslovakia in Chi\ncago, died last night at Presby\nterian hospital after an abdomi\nnal operation.\nNEW EARTH TREMORS\nMEXICO CITY. Dec. 28. <UP>\nSharp earth tremors rocked cen\ntral Mexico as far south us the\nIsthmus of Tehuantcoec yester\nday. The tremors were the most\nsevere since the major quake of\nlast Thursday.\nSURVEY WILL\nSHOW IF PANAYi\nCAN BE RAISED\nArriving at Reoarahons\nSeen as Next Step in\n^Incident\"\nFILM OF SINKING IS\nDUE !N U. S. TODAY\nSHANGHAI. Pre. 2K. (I'D\nThe 1'. .S. gunboat Oahu started\nup tlu> Yangtse riv\u00ab\u00bbr today for\nNankin?, whore it will determine\nwhether the sunken gunboat Pa\nnay can 5e raised.\nA IS? itish salvage tug accom\npanied the Oahu.\nMANY PROBLEMS\nTO RE ADJUSTED\nWASHINGTON. Pee. 28. I I1\n.Multiple problems touching such\ndelicate matters as placing a mon\netary value on a human life, con\nfronted the administration today\nas it prepared to move into the\nsecond phase of the \"Panav inci\ndent\"\u2014reparations from Japan.\nState department officials said\nthat indemnity negotiations have\nnot yet begun, explaining that tin*\nfortnight following the bombing\nand sinking of the V. S. S. gun\nboat Panay and three Standard\nOil steamers was devoted com\npletelv to fixing the blame and\nobtaining a satisfactory apology.\nAmong the issues entering into\nthe size of the bill which this- gov\nernment will present to the Japa\nnese. however, are:\nHow much money will be do-1\nmanded for the families of those\nkilled or wounded in the Panay\nbombing? In the past the govern\nment has demanded and received\n$25,000 for families of Cnited\nStates nationals who met death\nabroad under circumstances in\nwhich a foreign power paid repa\nrations.\nWill the value to be placed on\nthe lives of American sailors sac\nrificed in the incident be deter\nmined by their potential earning\npower in the fleet or in private\nlife?\nWill this government ask for a\nsum comparable to the original\ni'ost o f the Panay or what it would\ncost to build the craft today?\nWill the ships to replace the\nPanay and the oil steamers bo\nbuilt in America or with cheaper\nJapanese labor in the Orient\nWill these ships be built by the\nJapanese or b\\* Americans?\nThe Tokyo government has vol\nunteered to make full reparations.\nNegotiations are expected to be\nconducted dircctlv with Tokyo and\nofficials indicated it may be many\nweeks before a settlement is final\nly concluded.\nCAMERAN FLOWN\nTO U. S. WITH FILMS\nHON'OLUI.U. T. II., Die. 2X.\nUT>\u2014The Pan American China\nClipper, carrying the news reel\nfilms of the bombing and sinking\nof the American gunboat Panay\nabove Nanking, took off for San\nFrancisco at 3:54 p. m. (PST)\nyesterday.\nBoth films of Universal News\nreel and Fox-Movietone News\nwere aboard the ship, which was\ndue in San Francisco today.\nOne of the passengers was Nor\nman Alley, cameraman who took\nthe I'niversal pictures of the at\ntack on the Panay by Japanese\nwar planes.\nPoor flying conditions had held\nthe big airship at Honolulu for 21\nhours.\nThe J.\">00 feet of film, only pic\ntorial record of the incident, have\nbeen insured for $300,000 with\nLloyds.\nNavy Broadens West Coast Patrol;\nAlien Submarine Activities Rumored\nSAN PKDRO. Calif.. Dec. Ii8.\nI (UP)\u2014Humors of alien subma\nrine activity of! the California\ncoasts and the dispatch of a sec\nond squadron of nine naval Hr\nstroyers here from San Diego for\npatrol duty enlivened the navy's\nmysterious maneuvers in the Pa\ncific today.\nThe Los Angeles Daily News\nsaid today that navy authorities\nwere discussing reports that \"an\nalien flotilla of submarines, prob\nably Japanese,\" had been seen off\nthe coast.\nThe newspaper said the infor\nmation came from \"a man well\nversed in naval secrets both in\nCalifornia and Washington.\" and\nthat the informant said it was fea\nsible for Japanese submarines to\noperate from some secluded place\nalong the lower California coast.\nCommander C. J. Wheeler, sec\nretary to Admiral Arthur J. Hep\nburn, commander-in-chief of the\nfleet, denied the rumor.\n\"The navy has not taken any\nstock in it,\" Wheeler said. \"The\nreport is about aweek old, first\ndescribing only one submarine. It\nappears to have grown into a flo\ntilla.\"\nThe Los Angeles newspaper in\nformant said the navy had sent\nseaplanes to scout for the sub\nmarines. He did not say what the\n(Continued on page three)\nAdvised NLRB in Ford Dispute\nImportant in tin- National Labor\nRelations Iaction airaitist\nthe Ford Motor company which\nculminated in orders u\u00bb Ford to\n\"cease interferinjr\" with lahor\nunions, were farts Wrought out.\nby tin* XI.Kit counsel at St.\nLouis, shown at the hearing,\nAlan Perl. It'ft, Joseph A. Hos\nkins, center. and (I. Van Arkel.\nHAGUE PLEDGES TO DRIVE\nCIO, OUT OF JERSEY CITY\nVeteran Who Died Here\nWill Be Buried Near\nChesnee Wednesday\nSPARTANHl'RG. S. Dec. I\n2S.\u2014-James S. Kimbrell, one of'\nthe last six surviving Confederate)\nwar veterans of Spartanburg:\ncounty, died at ti\"* home of a\ndaughter, Mrs. K. I!. Sitton, at I\nllcndersonvillo, N'. yesterday\nafternoon after a lingering i! 1 no\u00ab>.\nMr. Kimbrell, who as a young\nman saw service with the (Confed\nerate army in the War Retwecn\nthe States, was in his IM.'trd year i\nat the time of his death.\nA devoted Christian and church\nworker, he had been a member of\nthe Trinity Methodist church, near\nChesnee, since early boyhood.\nFuneral services will be con\nducted at tin* Arrowwood Hap\nlist church, near Chesnee, at I:.'\u00bb()\no'clock Wednesday afternoon. In\nterment will be in the church\ncemetery.\nThe following grandsons will\nserve as active pallbearers: (\u00bbuy\nV. Sitton, Hubert Collins, Lester\nRobinson, Lee Kimbrell. hhmael\nKimhrcll and Hurt McGinnis.\nThe honorary escort will be\ncomposed of the following: I). P.\nL. Martin, Dr. S. 1). Reid. Sam\nTurner, A. Thompson, h'. C. Tan\nner, Jim Kakcr, J. L. Anderson.\nV. K. Hatchet te, N. L. Watson,\nS. L. Meredith, L\\ F. Wall. V.\nJolley, R. It. .lolley. A. Mossburg.\nF. II. Messner, T. Yassey, J. L.\nHarris, George Moore, Rev. W. (J.\nP. Kzell. J. C. Kzell. J. T. Jolley.\nW. W. Kzell. Cieorge Feagan, Dr.\nJ. H. Cash, Robert Crawford, and\nII. Ray.\nLESTER DILL IS\nBROUGHT HOME\nNew Warrants Are Served\nAfter Return From\nGreenville, S. C.\nLester Dill, wanted here for\njumping $100 b\u00abil on a traffic vio\nlation charge was brought from\nGreenville this morning by Sheriff\nW. E. Davis and placed in the\ncounty jail.\nDill was arrested on charges\nbrought by YY. M. Mill, bondsman,\nand after his arrival here was\nserved with warrants charging as\nsault on a female and forcible\ntrespass on the property of Mrs.\nP. G. Hart at Zirconia.\nSheriff Davis was notified that\nDill was in the Greenville jail by\nofficers there who arrested him\nfor assault.\nON FLORIDA VISIT\nMr. and Mrs. Guy Mitchell,\nwhose residence is on the Brevard\nroad a few miles from Henderson\nville, have gone to Florida for a\nstay of perhaps a month.\nSays Leaders Opposed to\nCity Boasting Freedom\nFrom Labor Disorder\nJ KKSKY CITY. J.. I iff. 28.\n(I'h Charging tint the Com\nmittee for Industrial Organization\nwas_Jrying to prevent industrial\nHants from locating here. Mayor\nFrank Hague last night called on\nthe people of Jersey City to \"aid\nmi* in my efforts tr\u00bb obstruct this\nlawless element.\"\nThere have ho\"ii frequent\nclashes between Hague and CIO\nlenders, and a few weeks ago Jer\nsey City police prevented mem\nbers of the organiza'ion from dis\ntributing pamphlets inside the city\nlimits.\n\"If the people of \\*ew Jersey\nstand behind me.\"' Hague said in\na formal statement, \"I can assure\nthem that before this campaign\nof violence and terrorism is ended\nI will bring to justice all those\nwho may be responsible for any\nunlawful attacks and violence in\nthis city.\"\nHague said that the leader \u00ab>f\nthe CIO movement in this city\nwas William Carney, a regional\ndirector, \"a man who comes from\nOhio and has lived here only a\nshort time.\"\nThe mayor's statement bore the\ncaption \"The real reasons behind\nthe CIO movement in Jersey\nCity.\"\n\"While uprisings and unrest\nwere prevalent throughout the\ncountry,\" lie said. \"Jersey City\nwas free of any disorder or labor\ntrouble contributing to this\nresult was the fact that we have\nalways required that industry not\nonly maintain proper working con\nditions for its employes, but that\nthe highest prevailing scale of\nwages should be paid to them.\nThey (CIO leaders) are\nopposed to any city which can\nboast about the absence of unrest\nand the freedom from labor dis\norder, Their principal method of\noperation is to create disorder; to\n(Continued on page three.)\nTVA Orders Wage\nIncrease And 40\nHour Work Week\nKNOX VILIJ5, Tenn., Dec. 28.\nM'P)\u2014The Tennessee Valley au\nthorit.v yesterday ordered effec\ntive January 1 an approximately\n5 per cent wage increase and a\n10-hour work week for its 8,000\nemployes hired by the hour in the\nTennessee river watershed.\nThe increased wages and short\ner hours were granted after col\nlective bargaining conferences\nduring the past six weeks between\nthe authority and the American\nFederation of Labor's T V A\nunions.\nThe agreement provides for\ntime and a half for overtime and\neven higher wages than the scale\nprovides, if necessary to meet pre\nvailing wages on similar projects\nin communities outside the water\nshed area where TVA employes\nare assigned to work.\nCost of the additional wages to\nthe TVA wa sestimated at more\nthan $500,000 annually. The larg\nest single increase was $180,000\nfor unskilled workers, whose rate\nwas increased from 45 to 47 1-2\ncents per hour.\nOHIO HEIRESS\nEXONORATED\nIN KILLING\nWoman Is Freed by Coron\ner's Jury; Mother Died i\nAfter Shooting\nOFFERED OWN BLOOD\nFOR TRANSFUSION\nWAURKN'. Ohio. J8. flJP)\nfouise Campbell, US, heiress to,\n'he Y<>u\u00bbKsto\\vn Sheet and Tube\nmillions today was exonerated in\nthe Christmas day shooting of\nher mother.\nA coroner's verdict of \"acci\ndental death\" ended Louise's\nthree-day hunger strike in jail.\nEvidence at the inquest all\npointed to accident.\nThe coroner said Mrs. ('amp\nhell was slain when she tried to\ntake a pistol from her daughter\nwho hiid been shooting at candles\non a Christmas tree.\nMiss Campbell swore yesterday\nthat she was taking a practice tar\nget shot at a candle on a Christ\nmas tree when she fired the bullet\nthat fatally wounded her mother.\nAfter hearing testimony, Cor\noner J. C. Henshaw of Trumbull\ncounty held Miss Campbell on an\nopen churuc and continued the\nhearing today.\nMiss Campbell testified that\nhe had drunk \"two or three egic\nnogs and some beer\" and that her\nmother tried to take the pistol\naway from her when she pointed\nit at the Christmas tree.\nThe tragedy occurred in the\nmidst Of a gay Christmas party,\nand today Miss Campbell fre\nquently brushed a handkerchief\nacross her eyes as she related the\ndetails to the coroner.\n\"1 levelled my pistol at a can\ndle on the tree,\" Miss Campbell\nsaid, \"and fired a shot. As 1 did\nso, mother turned from a large\ncenter table and attempted to\ntake the pistol away from me.\"\nMrs. Cordelia Campbell, 55,\nwidow of Louis J. Campbell, a\nfounder of the Youngstown Sheet\nand Tube company, was wounded\nin the abdomen. Miss Campbell\noffered to give blood to her moth\ner when a transfusion was indicat\ned, but Mrs. Campbell died.\nLucius Cochran, a friend, and\nMrs. L'retta Branch, Miss Camp\nbell'.. sister, corroborated her tes\ntimony concerning the number of\ndrinks she had taken.\nWOMAN 'MISSING,' ON\nYACHTING CRUISE\nNASSAU, X. P., BAHAMAS,\nDec. 28. (UP)\u2014Mis. Kthcl M.\nBroadwater, In, sought by police\nsinco her disappearance from her\nroom at the Victoria hotel here\nChristmas morning, returned to\nth.'! hotel last night and explained\nthat she had been on a yachting\ncruise.\nThe woman said that while\ncruising among the surrounding\nislands the yacht's wireless broke\ndown and she was unable to com\nmunicate with Nassau.\nJAKE KILRAIN DIED\nFROM COMPLICATIONS\nQI.'INCY, Mass., Doc. 28.\nUP). Cancer, heart disease,\ngangrene and hardening of the\narteries caused the death Wed\nnesday of Jake Kilrain, last of\nthe \"bare knuckle\" fighters who\nwent 7<r> rounds with John L. Sul\nlivan nearly a half century ago,\naccording to the death certificate\nfiled yesterday.\nKilrain would have been 7!\u00bb\nnext February 0. His 75-round\nbout with Sullivan was fought\nJuly K, 1H80, at Richburg, Miss.\nW.M. Drake, Near\nDeath Following\nExposure, Better\n\n\\V. .M. Drake, who became lost\nwhile bird huntintr and was car\nried to Patton Memorial hospital\nfor treatment on Saturday, left\nthe hospital this morning and was\nvery much improved.\nDrake was near death from\nsickness and cold when found by i\nsearching parties but after being'\ntreated at the hospital recovered.]\nHe was lost when he became ill\nwhile hunting and failed to reach\nhis car. A searching partv found\nhim and took him to th<* hospital.\nMaurice Ravel,\nFrench Composer\nIs Dead At 63\nPARIS, Dec. 28. <IT)\u2014Mau\nrice Ravel, internationally fa\nmous composer, died today.\nRavel, <)2, was one of the fore\nmost of living composers. Such of\nhis works as Daphnis and Chloe,\nThe Holcro, I.e Tombeau Dc Cou\nperin and others were familiar\nthroughout the world.\nHe was taken to a hospital last\nweek for an operation to combat\nan ailment which made it difficult\nfor him to write or otherwise use\nhis hands. He showed much im\nprovement at first but took a\ngrave turn for the worse Sunday.\nDuring recent months Ravel\nhad complained that though he\ncontinued, during walks in the\nwoods, to work out themes, he\nhad difficulty in reducing them to\npaper. His last work was a con\ncerto for the left hand, written\nseveral years ago.\nPianist and com|*>ser, Ravel\nwas born at Cibourne, near Miar\nritz. At 12 he began the serious\nstudy of the piano and soon show\ned such rapid and comprehensive\nprogress that his career was es\ntablished.\nAt the Paris conservatoire, Ra\nvel took a course in hatmony un\nder Pessard, studied counterpoint\nand fugue with Gedalze and then\nbecame a pupil in composition of\nGabriel Faurc.\nAt this time Ravel's marked\noriginality in composition became\nmanifest. In 190.'! he decided to\ntry for the Prix De Rome. Ho\nset the poem Myrrha to music and\njr\u00bbv<\u00ab it extmmely light treatment.\nWhen it came to be judged,\nCharles I/onepvue. member of the\ninstitute, protested:\n\"M. Ravel has the right, to take\nus for firemen, but not for imbo\ncil\u2122!\"\nRavel continued his work with\nzeal, but in semi-seclusion, after\nsuch attacks as this. However,\nsome newspapers and musical pub\nlications began to champion him.\nThe director of the conservatoire,\nresigned and Gabriel fraure, Ra\nvel's old teacher, succeeded. Ra\nvel's martyrdom ended promptly.\nHis fame spread rapidly and his\npopularity became universal.\nPlan New Year's\nDance At Skyland\nPlace for Junior Welfare\nEvent Changed\nThe annual New Year's dance:\nof the Junior Welfare club will\nbe held at the Skyland hotel in\nstead of the city gymnasium, it\nwas announced this morning.\nThe heating system in the new\ngym has not been completed and\nit was necessary to make the\nchange.\nA1 Dunn and his orchestra will\nplav for the dance on New Year's,\nEve.\nDeclares Farm Bill's Passage Would\nSpell Economic End Of Cotton South\nMONTGOMERY. A'a., Doc. 28.\n(UP)\u2014Passage of the present\nfarm bill in congress will mean\n\"economic death for the cotton\nsouth,\" Alabama's commissioner\nof agriculture Robert J. Goode\npredicted last night.\nGoode pointed out that the dan\nger lay in a provision in both the\nsenate and house bills which would\nprevent the farmer from using\nland diverted from cottwi and\nother items covered by the meas\nure. except for foodstuffs the fam\nily would consume.\nThe provision, he said, would\n\"prevent the use of acres diverted\nfrom cotton to the production of\nfood, feed and forage necessary\nfor the expansion of the livestock\nand dairy industry. It would seri\nously hamper the diversified pro\npram for agriculture.\"\nGoode cited as an example a\nfarmer with a 10-acre corn base.\nThe acreage would lie reduccd to\nseven, he said, and the farmer\ncould not use the extra three for\npasturajre, food or feed unless\nthe family consumed the entire\namount raised on the three-acre\ntract.\n\"If he invited his neighbor or\nhis preacher and fed them any\nproducts raised on this surplus\nthree acres,\" he continued, \"he\nwould actually be violating the\nlaw and be subject to penalty.\"\nNEW MESSAGE\nTO DEAL WITH\nBUSINESS AID\nGeneral Motors Will Lay\nOff 30,000 Men.Because\nof Recession\nROOSEVELT WANTS\n-CCC FUNDS PARED\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 28. (IT)\nAdministration loader* hero arn\nanticipating a presidential mes\nsage intended to guide congress\ntoward firm foreign and national\ndefense policies, a curb on monop\noly and business encouragement\nthrough tax revision to the new\ncongressional session opening Jan\nuary 3.\nThe message is expected be\na comprehensive disclosure of the\nadministration's program as it ap\npears after the fruitless special\nsession and in the fact* of the cur\nrent business recession. President\nRoosevelt is expected to call for\nsome form of revival of the\nwages and hours bill and may of\nfer a modification of his regional\nplanning bill, providing for seven\nnew TV A projects.\nGENERAL MOTORS TO\nLAY OFF 30,000 MEN\nDETROIT, Die. <UP\u00bb\nGeneral Motors today announced\na reduction in its working force\nof approximately 30,000 men ef\nfective Saturday.\nPresident William S. Knud^en,\nwho made the announcement,\nblamed the business recession.\nMost of the layoffs, he said, will\nbe in Michigan.\nPRICE STABILITY\nNO PRACTICAL HELP\nATLANTIC CITY, Dor. 28.\u2014\n(UP)\u2014Farmers would get littlo\nhelp through \"increased price\nstability,\" Dr. Joseph S. Davis, di\nrector of the Food Research In\nstitute of Stanford university,\nsaid here today in attacking Sec\nretary of Agriculture Wallace'*\never-normal granary plan.\nORIENTAL COTTON\nEXPORTS BOOSTED\nWASHINGTON, Dec 2*. ILT)\nThe department of agriculture to\nday *8id that American cotton is\ngoing to the orient in increasing\nquantities after months of low\nsales.\nChina obtained I2.H00 bale* in\nthe first throe weeks of December,\nafter eluding the Japanese block\nade.\nOnly 200 bales were exported\nfrom August to December.\nJapan also picked up in cotton\npurchase in early December.\nTotal exports since August I\nare 10 per cent greater than last\nyear, despite the 80 per cent re\nduction of oriental purchases.\nROOSEVELT WOULD\nTRIM CCC FUNDS\n(Copyright, 1937, United Pre**)\n..WASHINGTON, Dec. 28. (UP)\nPresident Roosevelt, putting re\nnewed pressure behind his govern\nmental economy and hudget-bal\nancing program, has asked con\ngress to slash 123,<588,000 from\nthe $350,000,000 Civilian Conser\nvation corps appropriation for the\n193'J fiscnl year, it was learned\n(Continued on page four)\nRebels Radioing\nFrantic Appeals\nThose at Teruel Prefer\nDeath to Surrender\nTKRUEL, Spain, by Courier\nvia Valverdc, Doc. 2H. (UP)\u2014A\nshort wave radio transmitter\nwithin the fire-swept civil govern\nor's palace last night crackled out\nfrantic appeals for aid from a\nband of insurgent soldiers and\ntheir women who are ready t<\u00bb die\nrather than surrender.\nThe radio pleas, sent monoto\nnously hour after hour, were pick\ned up by Generalissimo Francisco\nFranco's relief columns struggling\nto smash through the outer ring\nof steel which the government\nforged around this Aragoncsc city\nto entrap the rebel garribon.\n\"Keep up your spirits; remem\nber the Alcazar,\" the insurgent\nheadquarters of General Miguel\nAranda beyond the mountains to\nthe north radioed back.\nBut it was doubtful whether\nthe desperate band inside the\nruined palace of Teruel's \"old\ncity\" could hold out much longer\nbecause there was little water to\ndrink and none for fighting the\nflames caused by loyalist incen\ndiary shells that arc slowly anni\nhilating them.","height":"27723","width":"20715"}}
